Chadwick proposes increasing legal age to buy tobacco products







Tuesday
Sep 16, 2014 at 12:01 AM
Sep 16, 2014 at 11:37 AM






				By ANDREW DENNEYadenney@columbiatribune.com | 815-1719
			
First Ward Councilwoman Ginny Chadwick has called for Columbia to ban the use of e-cigarettes indoors and to increase the minimum age to buy tobacco products in the city to 21.The council unanimously passed a motion just after midnight on Tuesday at its regular meeting to send the legislative intent for Chadwick�s proposal to the city�s Board of Health and Substance Abuse Advisory Commission for review before a complete bill is presented to the council for a vote.Smoking in indoor public spaces has been banned in Columbia since 2007.In remarks during the council comments portion of the meeting agenda, in which council members are able to propose motions for a vote, Chadwick said raising the minimum age would lower the use of tobacco products by youth by making it easier to spot underage purchasers, decrease cultural acceptance of youth smoking and cut off peers� access to the products.�This decrease will create lasting benefits on the prevalence of tobacco use and save thousands of lives in Columbia,� Chadwick said.Jonathan Sessions, a member of the Columbia Board of Education, said he approached Chadwick with the idea of increasing the tobacco-sale age while she was still running for office earlier this year. Sessions said that because there are 18-year-old students at Columbia Public Schools, there is potential for students to legally acquire tobacco products and then distribute them to younger students.�It happened when I was in school, it happened, I�m sure, before I was in school, it happens to this day,� Sessions said.According to a Food and Drug Administration Center for Tobacco Products literature review released last December, there are a number of barriers to determining the toxicity of e-cigarettes: There is sparse data available on the effects of exposing humans to e-cigarettes, e-cigarette users also might use cigarettes � which can alter exposure levels � and some research has indicated that nicotine delivery levels from e-cigarettes can vary substantially even among devices within the same brand.Despite the dearth of available information about the product, advertising for e-cigarettes has been aggressive.According to an analysis of e-cigarette websites conducted this year by the San Francisco Center for Tobacco Control Research and Education, 95 percent of the websites made explicit health claims, 88 percent said the devices can be used anywhere and 64 percent mentioned smoking cessation.Dan Rader, a member of the Substance Abuse Advisory Commission and co-owner of Bengal�s Bar and Grill in downtown Columbia, said he thinks the proposals are a �step in the right direction.� The use of e-cigarettes by Bengal�s patrons has caused issues at the bar in the past, he said, as staff and fellow patrons have confused the devices with cigarettes.Additionally, Rader said he supports applying the same age restrictions that are in place for alcohol to tobacco products.�I think it�s become quite clear over time that cigarettes are harmful,� Rader said. �Bringing that minimum age more in line with the minimum age for alcohol, it makes sense.�













